\begin_layout Standard
This should not surprise anyone familiar with the current state of economic
 geography.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Strictly speaking, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

economic geography
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 refers to a sub-discipline of geography, but here I use it more broadly
 to include certain strains of urban studies outside the discipline of geography
 proper.
 I believe the description of the current state of economic geography presented
 here applies outside the discipline of geography as much as inside.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Since the late 1980's, the field has become increasingly fragmented and
 disconnected 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "scott07economic,barnes2010nothing"

\end_inset

.
 Rapid, geographically discontinuous change became common in the global
 space economy, making the economic prospects of what had previously been
 the economically secure and dominant 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

core
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of the global economy increasingly tenuous and uncertain.
 This motivated economic geographers to look for (and often claim they had
 discovered) the next new thing that could save homeland capitalism, and
 economic geography went through a corresponding series of faddish 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

turns
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (technological, flexible, cultural, relational, evolutionary, etc.).
 It became preoccupied with 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the churn and chop of capitalist restructuring,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 but paying little or no attention to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the structural dynamics of that churn and chop
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "11"
key "peck2016macroeconomic"

\end_inset

.
 Its gaze settled on the local and regional, the micro and meso, the new
 and novel.
 This became so characteristics of the field that in his response to 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeauthor
key "hudson2016risingpowers"

\end_inset

's 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyearpar
key "hudson2016risingpowers"

\end_inset

 account of ongoing transformations in the global economy, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Peck_2016_Macroeconomic"

\end_inset

 stresses how uncommon 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

macroscopic questions
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 like the ones 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeauthor
key "hudson2016risingpowers"

\end_inset

 addresses have become in contemporary economic geography.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fn:macroeconomic"

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeauthor
key "peck2016macroeconomic"

\end_inset

's otherwise excellent commentary has two unfortunate characteristics.
 The term 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

macroeconomic
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in the title evokes a sense of how both mainstream and heterodox economists
 practice macroeconomics within the discipline of economics.
 For the most part, they study the structures of whole economies, the articulati
on of the component parts of such structures, and their dynamics.
 While 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeauthor
key "hudson2016risingpowers"

\end_inset

's paper presumes such elements, they are mainly implicit.
 Instead, the paper is an interpretive description of ongoing changes in
 the global economy.
 So the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

macroeconomic
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 label could be misleading.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Second, in discussing the novelty of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeauthor
key "hudson2016risingpowers"

\end_inset

's intervention, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeauthor
key "Peck_2016_Macroeconomic"

\end_inset

 briefly recounts the history of economic geography since the 1970's.
 In doing so he metaphorically borrows a practice from computer software
 development, calling the prevalent academic practice during the period
 from around 1970 to the mid-1990's 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

economic geography 1.0
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and the (multiple, fragmented, isolated) practices during the subsequent
 period, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

economic geography 2.0.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 But in computer software such nomenclature typically connotes improvement
 in subsequent generations, in the sense that they correct earlier errors
 (fix bugs) and enhance capabilities.
 But neither characteristic is self-evident in economic geography as practiced
 since the 1990's.
 In fact, a good case can be made that the second phase is retrograde.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Cite articles in the new handbook when you get it.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 Furthermore, as the field became fragmented, debates between devotees of
 different approaches occasionally became acrimonious, and this combined
 with the tendency for inbreeding within approaches, not only to further
 fragment the field, but also to turn different approaches into self-referential
, self-reinforcing 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

intellectual solitudes
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "barnes2010nothing"

\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

tribes
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "peck2012economic"

\end_inset

.
 Although no comprehensive study of the methodology underpinning the field's
 current research practice exists, it is hard to resist the suspicion that
 eclectic and ad-hoc is common.
 Finally, much as the flexible specialization literature asserts firms avoid
 making major capital investments in turbulent economic environments 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "piore1984thesecond"

\end_inset

, in the turbulent environment of academic Anglophone economic geography,
 researchers are prone to choose topics requiring smaller, less risky investment
s.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This may be especially true for younger scholars.
 Studying the structural dynamics of capitalism requires some familiarity
 with mainstream macroeconomics and its heterodox counterpoints, as well
 as enough mathematics both to make one's way through this often math-laden
 literature and to conduct independent research.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "490"
key "scott07economic"

\end_inset

 notes that scholars trained during economic geography's quantitative phase
 often transitioned later to doing political-economic research on broad
 structural dynamics.
 Even though they rejected the positivism and apologetics of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

spatial science,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 their knowledge of the mainstream literature and their quantitative training
 served them well for this task.
 But after twenty-five years of fragmentation, things have changed.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "119"
key "peck2012economic"

\end_inset

 suggests economic geography has experienced a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

generational shift towards more qualitative approaches.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 If so, then younger scholars today may be ill-equipped for studying capitalism'
s macro-structural dynamics and choose to confine themselves to topics amenable
 to qualitative research at micro- and meso- levels..
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Rigor can be a casualty of this proclivity to make small investments combined
 with the rush to join the latest fad, and observers have noted that the
 quality of recent research often leaves much to be desired 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "markusen1fuzzyconcepts,martin2001rethinking"

\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
On top of this, the field's ventures into such things as poststructuralism
 and postmodernism introduced widely varying standards of what legitimately
 counts as high-quality research.
 In such an environment, what is one person's rigor is another's rigor mortis.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
But the bigger point is that economic geography today is nowhere near the
 ideal of a scientific community, joined together around the common goal
 of developing a shared understanding of the world by building on a common
 research program, focusing on a consensual set of questions, and finding
 ways to adjudicate disagreements.
 In this context, the likelihood that even a subset of contemporary economic
 geographers would identify potential threats to the global economic order,
 consistently monitor such threats, and based on such research warn about
 the order's immanent implosion is virtually nil.
 Mainstream economics may be autistic ??, but economic geography suffers
 from attention deficit disorder.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Nonetheless, despite its disorder and fragmentation, certain unifying threads
 run through contemporary economic geography.
 These include the shared beliefs that capitalism is neither universal nor
 superior to other forms of economic organization; that capitalism is necessaril
y subject to crises and generally in a state of disequilibrium; that there
 is no such thing as a separate, self-governing 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

economy,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 but instead 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

economic
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 aspects of society are always embedded in a wider social web of culture,
 institutions, ecology, and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

nature
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

; that spatiality matters in that space cannot be reduced to a Cartesian
 container but instead is intrinsic to human life, and the social, historical,
 and spatial aspects of human societies constitute and determine each other
 in a socio-spatial dialectic; that society is not an undifferentiated collectio
n of individuals, much less one with common goals and bound together by
 social contracts or other forms of mutual consent, but instead consists
 of social relations of unequal power along various axes of domination/subordina
tion; and that concrete research on actual economies in specific places
 is particularly important.
 (See
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealt
key "sheppard2011geographical,sheppard2012thelong,peck2016macroeconomic"

\end_inset

; and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealt
key "soja1980thesociospatial"

\end_inset

.) These shared beliefs situate economic geography in opposition to mainstream
 economic orthodoxy thereby qualifying economic geography as heterodox relative
 to mainstream economics 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Peck_2015_Navigating,sheppard00000heterodox"

\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeauthor
key "Peck_2015_Navigating"

\end_inset

sees such unorthodox beliefs and practices as a weak qualification for being
 heterodox and points to economic geography's pluralism as stronger qualificatio
n.
 But on its own pluralism per se does not qualify a set of practices as
 heterodox, and in fact some authors claim mainstream economics is already
 pluralist and becoming more so.
 See below.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 But these beliefs are very general and therefore leave room for great variation
 in the practice of economic geography, so these threads tying economic
 geography together are quite loose.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Marxism is possibly a stronger thread.
 David Harvey's brilliant work 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "esp."
key "harvey2006thelimits"

\end_inset

 has been remarkably influential in the field, and he has steadfastly promoted
 and advanced the Marxist tradition in geography.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "sheppard2012thelong"

\end_inset

 maintain that 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

anyone seeking to take economic geography in a new and different direction
 still feels compelled to rationalize their position relative to his [Harvey's],
 either to declare affinities to, or distance themselves from, Harvey and
 Marxism.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeauthor
key "sheppard2011geographical"

\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyear
key "sheppard2011geographical"

\end_inset

, 320; 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealt
after "11"
key "sheppard2012thelong"

\end_inset

) thus describes the field as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

haunted by Marx.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Sheppard cites 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "derrida25specters"

\end_inset

 as the source of this term.
 But my own reading of Derrida's book is that its title refers to the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

spectre
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 that Marx and Engels described as haunting Europe at the beginning of the
 
\emph on
Communist Manifesto
\emph default
 (i.e., communism), and Derrida's book (which originally was a lecture) is
 about using post-structuralism as a tool to identify something in today's
 world that could serve a similar role as a radical liberation movement.
 In relation to this, Derrida identifies ten 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

plagues
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of today's global capitalism.
 But in keeping with this obviously religious allusion, much of Derrida's
 book deals with similar religious and supernatural allusions in Marx.
 To me the most memorable and dramatic of these (and the most relevant to
 this paper) is the image of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

an enchanted, perverted, topsy-turvy world, in which Monsieur le Capital
 and Madame la Terre do their ghost-walking as social characters and at
 the same time directly as mere things
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "830"
key "marx1967capital"

\end_inset

.
 Nonetheless, the practice of describing Derrida as himself being 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

haunted
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 by Marx in that he (Dirrida) had to deal with Marx, and describing other
 authors the same way, perhaps with some deliberate irony, is not uncommon.
 For example, without reference to Derrida, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "walker2004thespectre"

\end_inset

 uses similar imagery specifically with respect to David Harvey's influence
 on geography.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 This metaphor is very apropos.
 Many contemporary economic geographers treat not only Marx but the entire
 Marxist tradition more like a corpse than as something living and evolving.
 Hence, in post-1990 economic geography one finds almost zero references
 to new developments within Marxian economics, such as new, non-equilibrium,
 non-dual interpretations of the labor theory of value 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "freeman2010trendsin"

\end_inset

 or the copious literature rethinking Marx's theory of money in relation
 to production 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "graziani2003themonetary,wray1999theories"

\end_inset

; conversely, today very few economic geographers – even, or especially,
 those whose work is very much in a Marxist vein – make much effort to present
 their work as extending or modifying received Marxian political economy.
 Even around 1990, when the then-dominant 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

structuralist
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Marxian geographical political economy came under increasing criticism
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "scott07economic"

\end_inset

, few critics sought to reconcile their criticisms with the received approach
 by correcting or augmenting it.
 This was despite the fact that the critics were often sympathetic in that
 they shared with the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

structuralists
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 the inclination to reject spatial science's technocratic impulse in favor
 of a broader project of human liberation, and their criticisms of the received
 approach often maintained it was incomplete and too restrictive rather
 than incorrect .
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Incomplete by ignoring or downplaying class conflict, gender, human subjectivity
 and agency, non-capitalist elements in existing economies, and so on.
 Of course, an approach that is incomplete very likely will be unable to
 explain empirical situations on its own, and the causal efficacy of what
 it claims to know will depend on what elements it omits.
 So in this sense that structural logic was (mis)applied to certain situations,
 the approach was incorrect.
 Besides this, perhaps the main substantive criticism of the approach per
 se is that it was insufficiently open.
 See 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "490 - 491"
key "scott07economic"

\end_inset

.
 Of course, this is a gross generalization, but overall I think the characteriza
tion is correct.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is not to deny that some economic geographers, most notably David Harvey,
 continue to work in an explicitly Marxist frame, or that ideas from Marxist
 political economy permeate much of contemporary economic geography.
 Instead, the point is that economic geography has mostly shifted its focus
 to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the meso- and micro-scales
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "700"
key "jones2016geographies"

\end_inset

, which in itself is not problematic except insofar as the larger, macro-level
 disappears and these other scales appear as context-independent, free from
 any larger forces, and all there is.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The term 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

macro
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is ambiguous in that it is used to refer to large geographic scales (e.g.,
 global or continental) or to entire economies, which could be at much smaller
 scales (e.g., Chile or Sweden).
 Also see note 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
ref{fn:macroeconomic}
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Furthermore, without explicit consideration of the macro 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

purist
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 geographical political economy and heterodox macroeconomics, one has the
 sense that economic geography runs the danger of borrowing theoretical
 concepts in an eclectic, ad hoc manner, with little concern for coherence,
 much less a coherent, cumulative research program.
 It may well be that under certain conditions scientific fields benefit
 from being open to extreme diversity and pluralism, but surely scientific
 progress implies that at some point a given field coalesces around shared
 acceptance of a specific paradigm 
\emph on
within which
\emph default
 there may still be diversity, or there even may be multiple paradigms within
 a live-and-let-live arrangement, but there is not an almost random, diverse
 pluralism, with no shared coherence whatsoever.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "feyerabend1993against"

\end_inset

 be damned.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Turning to land rent, one sees a similar pattern.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ward2016theshitty"

\end_inset

distinguish between land and ground rent.
 The former includes payments for the use of not only land but also of buildings
 and other improvements associated with particular parcels of land.
 Ground rent, on the other hand, consists of payments for the use of land
 net of payments for the use of fixed capital on the land.
 Generally, a parcel of land's location is reflected in land-rent, but the
 portion of the payment attributable to location is usually treated as solely
 due to the location of the land even though improvements are located there
 too.
 Therefore, in urban contexts, location is thought to be captured by ground
 rent, and since the literature emphasizes location, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

ground rent
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 plays the central role.
 Nonetheless, this terminology is not used universally, and improvements
 on land also capture locational advantages (e.g., a gas station near a freeway
 offramp); furthermore, in a very real sense improvements 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

make
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 location (e.g.
 a skyscraper office building helps define 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

downtown.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) In other words, the relation between improvements and location is dialectical,
 and land rent not so easily split apart.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 After earlier periods of consensus during the 1970s and transition during
 the early 1980s, the study of land rent ruptured in the late 1980s 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "haila1990thetheory"

\end_inset

.
 In one respect, it broke into two camps: one 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

ideographic
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and emphasizing empirical research on specific situations, and the other,
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

nomothetic
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 camp emphasizing more general theorization.
 Along another axis of fragmentation, some authors emphasized land rent's
 role in accumulation, while others emphasized its coordinating role.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "276"
key "haila1990thetheory"

\end_inset

 also identifies a contradiction between research motivated by contemporary
 issues but often falling back on 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

canonical dogma
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and sees the field as being at a crossroads, either continuing in this
 vein or developing theory 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

in an unbiased manner.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Since the study of land rent is subject to the same currents as the larger,
 parent field of economic geography, it is unsurprising that this bifurcation
 occurred around the same time as when centrifugal forces and fragmentation
 became pronounced throughout economic geography.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, unlike the rest of economic geography, which shattered into so
 many fragments, the study of land rent entered a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

magic roundabout
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of circular reasoning 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "kerr1996thetheory"

\end_inset

 that effectively functioned as a theoretical and methodological cul-de-sac,
 followed by disinterest and neglect of the subject 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "park2014landrent,ward2016theshitty,christophers2016forreal"

\end_inset

.
 A good indicator of this disappearance from economic geography is land
 rent's virtual absence from contemporary textbooks and surveys of the field
 at all levels, from introductory to advanced 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "mackinnon2011introduction,wood2012economic,barnes2012thewileyblackwell"

\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "anderson2012economic"

\end_inset

 textbook is an interesting exception.
 Unlike most other contemporary textbooks, its center is spatial science,
 and it has barely a hint of geographical political economy.
 Even so, its sources concerning land rent all seem several decades old.
 This is difficult to determine with certainty because the book has a large
 list of references, it generally does not cite sources in the body of the
 text.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 And this neglect is not confined to economic geography: similar patterns
 of disinterest and neglect for land rent, as well as most forms of rentier
 income, can be found in such cognate fields as heterodox economics (Hudson
 and Bezemer 2012) and critical organization studies (Bohm, Land, and Beverugen
 2012).
\end_layout

