\begin_layout Standard
Evidence regarding Marx also undermines Chrisotphers' argument.
 If Marx's treatment of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

fictitious capital
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 caused disinterest in all things fictitious, particularly land rent, then
 one would expect periods with high interest in Marx to be marked by disinterest
 in land rent.
 This is clearly not the case.
 During the two decades from 1970 through 1990 interest in Marxian political
 economy among economic geographers was at perhaps its highest point 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "488 - 491"
key "scott07economic"

\end_inset

; yet this period was also one of intense interest in land rent 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "haila1990thetheory"

\end_inset

.
 Furthermore, false beliefs are a central theme – arguably the central theme
 – in Marx's project.
 He wrote about many false beliefs and practices based on such fictions:
 ideology, religion, commodity fetishism, etc.
 In fact, explaining how social systems necessarily generate particular
 fictions (i.e., false beliefs) is one of the hallmarks of critical social
 science 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "sayer1critical"

\end_inset

.
 On top of this, Marx himself originally (in 1857) planned to devote an
 entire book of 
\emph on
Capital
\emph default
 to land rent, and although he repeatedly changed the outline for his opus
 over the next decade, as late as the 1870s he was still working on the
 subject 
